## 3. Technical Grounding: Wikipedia Definitions

### 3.1 Core Photography Concepts

**Photography** is the art, application, and practice of creating durable images by recording light, either electronically via an image sensor or chemically via a light-sensitive material such as photographic film. The word comes from the Greek words *phos* ("light") and *graphé* ("drawing"), together meaning "drawing with light."

**Camera** is an optical instrument that captures visual images. At a basic level, cameras consist of a sealed box with a lens, a shutter, and a light-sensitive surface (film or digital sensor). Modern digital cameras use electronic image sensors to record images.

**Digital single-lens reflex camera (DSLR)** is a digital camera that combines the optics and mechanisms of a single-lens reflex camera with a digital imaging sensor. It uses a mirror mechanism to direct light from the lens to an optical viewfinder, then moves the mirror out of the way when the shutter is released to expose the sensor.

**Mirrorless interchangeable-lens camera (MILC)** is a digital camera with an interchangeable lens mount but no reflex mirror or pentaprism. Light passes directly to the image sensor, and the image is displayed on an electronic viewfinder (EVF) or rear LCD screen.

### 3.2 Exposure Triangle Concepts

**Aperture** is a hole or an opening through which light travels. In photography, it refers to the diameter of the lens opening that controls the amount of light reaching the film or sensor. Measured in f-stops (f/1.4, f/2, f/2.8, f/4, f/5.6, f/8, f/11, f/16, f/22), a smaller f-number indicates a larger opening (more light) and shallower depth of field.

**Shutter speed** is the length of time the camera's shutter is open, exposing light onto the camera sensor (or film). Expressed in seconds or fractions of a second, fast speeds (1/1000s) freeze motion while slow speeds (1/30s or longer) create motion blur.

**Film speed/ISO** is a measure of the sensitivity of photographic film or digital image sensor to light. Standard ISO values include 100, 200, 400, 800, 1600, 3200, 6400. Higher ISO values allow shooting in low light but introduce digital noise or film grain.

**Exposure (photography)** is the amount of light per unit area reaching an electronic image sensor or photographic film, as determined by shutter speed, aperture, and ISO sensitivity. The exposure triangle describes the relationship between these three variables.

### 3.3 Lens and Optical Concepts

**Focal length** is a measure of how strongly a lens converges (focuses) or diverges light. It is the distance from the optical center of the lens to the image sensor when the lens is focused at infinity. Shorter focal lengths (e.g., 24mm) provide wider angles of view; longer focal lengths (e.g., 200mm) provide narrower angles and greater magnification.

**Depth of field** is the distance between the nearest and farthest objects in a scene that appear acceptably sharp in an image. It is controlled by aperture (wider aperture = shallower depth of field), focal length (longer = shallower), subject distance (closer = shallower), and sensor size (larger sensor = shallower for same framing).

**Photographic lens** is an optical lens or assembly of lenses used in conjunction with a camera body to make images. Types include prime lenses (fixed focal length) and zoom lenses (variable focal length). Key specifications include focal length, maximum aperture, lens mount, and optical construction.

**Prime lens** is a photographic lens with a fixed focal length, offering wider maximum apertures (f/1.4, f/1.8), sharper image quality, and lighter weight compared to zooms of equivalent optical quality.

**Zoom lens** is a lens with a variable focal length allowing the photographer to change magnification without moving the camera position. Types include wide-angle zooms, standard zooms, telephoto zooms, and superzooms.

**Wide-angle lens** has a focal length shorter than the diagonal of the film or sensor format, typically under 35mm for full-frame, providing a wider field of view.

**Telephoto lens** has a focal length longer than the diagonal of the film or sensor format, typically 70mm or longer for full-frame, providing magnification and compressed perspective.

### 3.4 Camera Accessories Concepts

**Photographic lighting** refers to the illumination of scenes for photography, which can be natural (sunlight) or artificial (studio strobes, speedlights, continuous lights). Light modifiers include softboxes, umbrellas, reflectors, and diffusers.

**Tripod** is a three-legged stand used to stabilize a camera, essential for long exposures, time-lapse photography, and macro work. Materials include aluminum (heavy, affordable) and carbon fiber (light, expensive, vibration-dampening).

**Image stabilization** is technology that reduces blurring associated with camera shake. Types include optical/ lens-based (IS/VR/OSS) where floating lens elements compensate for movement, and in-body (IBIS) where the image sensor moves.

**Memory card** is an electronic flash memory data storage device used for storing digital media. Types include SD (Secure Digital), CompactFlash, CFexpress, and XQD. SD card speed classes include Class 2/4/6/10, UHS Speed Class U1/U3, and Video Speed Class V6-V90.

**Camera bag** is a protective carrying case designed to hold camera equipment, featuring padded dividers for organization. Types include backpacks, messenger/sling bags, shoulder bags, rolling bags, and holster bags.

**Flash (photography)** is a device that produces a brief, intense burst of artificial light, typically at 5500K color temperature (daylight balanced). Types include built-in pop-up flash, external speedlights (hot shoe flash), and studio strobes/monolights.

**Camera accessory** encompasses any supplementary item that enhances functionality, including lens filters (UV, polarizer, ND), battery grips, remote shutter releases, external flashes, microphones, and cleaning kits.

### 3.5 Additional Technical Concepts

**Exposure value (EV)** is a number that represents a combination of aperture and shutter speed that yields the same exposure. Each EV step represents a doubling or halving of light.

**Hyperfocal distance** is the closest distance at which a lens can be focused while keeping objects at infinity acceptably sharp. Used in landscape photography to maximize depth of field.

**RAW image format** contains minimally processed data from the image sensor, providing greater dynamic range and editing flexibility compared to JPEG.

**Macro photography** is extreme close-up photography of small subjects, typically at magnifications of 1:1 or greater (life-size or larger on the sensor).

**Bokeh** refers to the aesthetic quality of the blur in out-of-focus areas of an image, influenced by aperture blade design and lens optical characteristics.

**Crop factor** is the ratio of a full-frame sensor's diagonal to a smaller sensor's diagonal. For APS-C sensors, typical crop factors are 1.5x (Nikon, Sony, Fujifilm) or 1.6x (Canon), and 2x for Micro Four Thirds.

